# WHAT IT IS
#   `modbus-ws` solves the canonical "I want a browser-based
#   industrial-automation dashboard / HMI / debugger that talks
#   directly to a Modbus device" problem.  Modern browsers can't
#   open raw TCP sockets or serial ports — they can only do
#   HTTP fetches and WebSocket connections.  `modbus-ws` runs as
#   a small bridge daemon on a host that DOES have access to the
#   Modbus device (either via a USB-RS485 serial adapter or
#   via the local network's Modbus TCP server) and exposes a
#   JSON-RPC-style protocol over WebSocket that browsers can use
#   to issue Modbus read/write operations:
#
#     # In the browser:
#     var ws = new WebSocket('ws://gateway.example.org:3000');
#     ws.send(JSON.stringify({
#       type:       'readHoldingRegisters',
#       unit:       1,             // Modbus slave ID
#       address:    100,           // register address
#       length:     4,             // qty of registers
#       requestId:  'req-1'
#     }));
#     ws.onmessage = function(e) {
#       // {requestId:"req-1", data:[1,2,3,4]}
#     };
#
#   `modbus-ws` also bundles an HTTP server (`--nohttp` disables
#   it) that serves the canonical `node-modbus-ws-frontend` HTML
#   reference UI, a 3D-printable browser-based Modbus debugger
#   that lets you point-and-click read/write any register on the
#   connected device.
#
#   Use cases:
#
#     • Browser-based industrial HMIs (replace SCADA/HMI vendor
#       lock-in with a web frontend talking to modbus-ws)
#     • Live monitoring dashboards (Grafana doesn't speak Modbus
#       directly; modbus-ws + a small frontend bridges the gap)
#     • Embedded Modbus debugging (USB-RS485 adapter + Raspberry
#       Pi + modbus-ws → fully browser-accessible Modbus debugger)
#     • CI/integration testing of Modbus devices (a test script
#       speaks WebSocket to modbus-ws → modbus-ws speaks Modbus
#       to the device under test)
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from bin/modbus-ws.js commander
#                       `.option(...)` registrations; extracted
#                       via raw.githubusercontent.com fetch of
#                       bin/modbus-ws.js)
#
#   modbus-ws [OPTIONS]
#
#   Options:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Show version
#     -s, --serial <PORT>            Use serial port (set port,
#                                    e.g. `/dev/ttyUSB0` or
#                                    `COM3`)
#                                    [default: false]
#     -b, --baudrate <BAUD>          Set serial port baud rate
#                                    [default: 9600]
#                                    [common values: 1200, 2400,
#                                     4800, 9600, 19200, 38400,
#                                     57600, 115200]
#     -i, --ip <IP>                  Use TCP/IP (set slave URL
#                                    or IP address)
#                                    [default: false]
#     -P, --tcpport <PORT>           Server (this bridge's
#                                    WebSocket/HTTP) port number
#                                    [default: 3000]
#     -c, --nocache                  Do not use caching for
#                                    Modbus communication
#                                    [default: false]
#     -w, --nohttp                   Run only the WebSocket
#                                    server (skip the bundled
#                                    HTTP web server)
#                                    [default: false]
#     -m, --maxlength <NUMBER>       Max registers/coils to read
#                                    in one Modbus request
#                                    [default: 10]
#
#   Examples:
#     modbus-ws --ip 192.168.1.24
#         bridge to a Modbus TCP slave
#     modbus-ws --serial /dev/ttyUSB0
#         bridge to a Modbus RTU slave via a serial port
#     modbus-ws
#         (no serial/IP) — bridge to a simulated test slave
#     modbus-ws --ip 192.168.1.24 --nocache
#         bridge without the register-value cache
#     modbus-ws --ip 192.168.1.24 --nocache --nohttp
#         WebSocket-only bridge (no bundled HTTP server)
