# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `yaacov/node-modbus-ws` declares a **direct** dependency on
#   `modbus-serial@^8.0.1` in its `package.json` (verified via
#   `gh api repos/yaacov/node-modbus-ws/contents/package.json`).
#   Both packages are maintained by **the same author** —
#   Yaacov Zamir — making node-modbus-ws **the canonical
#   reference application demonstrating modbus-serial's idiomatic
#   use** for any developer learning the library.
#
#   `modbus-serial` (`yaacov/node-modbus-serial`) is **THE
#   canonical TypeScript / JavaScript Modbus library** — Yaacov
#   Zamir's reference pure-Node.js implementation of both Modbus
#   TCP and Modbus RTU client + server, in continuous active
#   development since 2014, with 600+ ★ on GitHub and 80,000+
#   weekly npm downloads.  It is the **dominant Modbus
#   dependency in the entire Node.js ecosystem** — the only
#   feature-complete + maintained pure-JS Modbus library on
#   npm (the alternatives — `modbus-tcp`, `node-modbus` (the
#   stephan-strate fork), `jsmodbus`, `modbus-stream` — are
#   either feature-limited, abandoned, or wrap libmodbus via
#   native bindings rather than implementing pure-JS).
#
#   `modbus-serial` exposes:
#
#     • Typed `ModbusRTU` class (the unified client constructor
#       — despite the name, also handles Modbus TCP and Modbus
#       ASCII):  `new ModbusRTU()` then one of the typed
#       transport openers `client.connectTCP(host, options)` /
#       `client.connectTcpRTUBuffered(host, options)` /
#       `client.connectTelnet(host, options)` /
#       `client.connectRTU(serialPort, options, next)` /
#       `client.connectRTUBuffered(serialPort, options, next)` /
#       `client.connectAsciiSerial(serialPort, options, next)` /
#       `client.connectRTUSocket(socketObject, next)`
#     • Typed unit-address setter `client.setID(unitId)` for
#       switching the active Modbus slave-address mid-session
#     • Typed timeout setter `client.setTimeout(ms)`
#     • Typed read operations — `client.readCoils(addr, qty)`
#       (FC 0x01) /  `readDiscreteInputs(addr, qty)` (FC 0x02) /
#       `readHoldingRegisters(addr, qty)` (FC 0x03) /
#       `readInputRegisters(addr, qty)` (FC 0x04)
#     • Typed write operations — `writeCoil(addr, val)` (FC 0x05)
#       /  `writeCoils(addr, vals)` (FC 0x0F) /  `writeRegister
#       (addr, val)` (FC 0x06) /  `writeRegisters(addr, vals)`
#       (FC 0x10) /  `writeFC10(unitID, addr, vals)` typed write
#       operations
#     • Typed report-server-id (FC 0x11) `client.reportServerID()`,
#       mask-write-register (FC 0x16) `client.writeFC22(unitID,
#       addr, andMask, orMask)`, read-FIFO (FC 0x18)
#       `client.readFC24(unitID, addr, qty)`, get-comm-event-counter
#       (FC 0x0B), read-exception-status (FC 0x07) typed special-
#       function-code operations
#     • Typed `Promise`-based + `Callback`-based dual API
#       surface throughout
#     • Built-in pure-JS server side: `client.startServerTCP(...)`,
#       `client.startServerRTU(...)` — for emulating Modbus
#       slaves in test fixtures or for bridging non-Modbus
#       data sources onto Modbus
#     • Typed `error.modbusCode` exception-code attribute on
#       thrown errors with the typed `ExceptionCodes.{
#       ILLEGAL_FUNCTION = 0x01, ILLEGAL_DATA_ADDRESS = 0x02,
#       ILLEGAL_DATA_VALUE = 0x03, SERVER_DEVICE_FAILURE = 0x04,
#       ACKNOWLEDGE = 0x05, SERVER_DEVICE_BUSY = 0x06,
#       MEMORY_PARITY_ERROR = 0x08,
#       GATEWAY_PATH_UNAVAILABLE = 0x0A,
#       GATEWAY_TARGET_DEVICE_FAILED_TO_RESPOND = 0x0B}` named
#       constants
